"Myslím, že na místa, kde se odvíjely rozhodující události našich životů, stojí za to občas zavítat, abychom zjistili: nemáme sami se sebou nic společného.\n\n- Imre Kertész, Yo, Otro. Crónica del Cambio\n|\nHis hope wasn't lost, it was buried, and somehow Prudence Ryland made that old grave seem much more shallow than it once was.\n\n- Kathryn\n|\nAmerica used to live by the motto 'Father Knows Best.' Now we're lucky if 'Father Knows He Has Children.' We've become a nation of sperm donors and baby daddies.\n\n- Stephen Colbert, I Am America\n|\nLife & Death are beyond our control. We can’t control where, how, or when we are born & we can’t control where, how, or when we may die. Then why Worry about it.\n\n- RVM\n|\nThere ain't no way you can hold onto something that wants to go, you understand? You can only love what you got while you got it.\n\n- Kate DiCamillo, Because of Winn-Dixie\n|\nHow can you tell? That I like books, I mean.The look on your face when you walked in, somehow I doubted you were that impressed by me.\n\n- Cassandra Clare, City of Bones\n|\nYou must find your own gift, the activity you are fond of and the activity you were created for\n\n- Sunday\n|\nA key to the brighter future is to reassess goals, priorities and do best to make things happen.\n\n- Martin\n|\nShe had walked to the brink, abandoning all belief, and just before the bitter end, she was pulled from the abyss by faith.\n\n- Sage Steadman, Upon Destiny's Song\n|\nSometimes when you lose your way, you find YOURSELF.\n\n- Mandy Hale, The Single Woman: Life, Love, and a Dash of Sass\n|\nIf you have two friends in your lifetime, you're lucky. If you have one good friend, you're more than lucky.\n\n- S.E.\n|\nLife, although it may only be an accumulation of anguish, is dear to me, and I will defend it.\n\n- Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley, Frankenstein\n|\nThe walls were lined with books, many of them in foreign languages, like insulation against the immediate present.\n\n- Ross\n|\nWith age comes wisdom, but sometimes age comes alone.\n\n- Oscar\n|\nAs the light begins to intensify, so does my misery, and I wonder how it is possible to hurt so much when nothing is wrong.\n\n- Tabitha Suzuma, Forbidden\n|\nThough I think and speak of greater becoming, I, too, am an infinite work in progress.\n\n- T.F. Hodge, From Within I Rise: Spiritual Triumph Over Death and Conscious Encounters with 'The Divine Presence'\n|\nFor the senses wander, and when one lets the mind follow them, it carries wisdom away like a windblown ship on the waters.\n\n- Anonymous, The Bhagavad Gita\n|\nThe truth, finally, is who can tell it.\n\n- Chang-rae Lee, Native Speaker\n|\nI want to learn. I deserve to read and write. Thoughts for company, and a pen for a voice. Who is more entitled to those privileges than I?\n\n- Julie Berry, All the Truth That's in Me\n|\nIn the end, we always regret the life we failed to live.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nI do not wish to comment on the work; if it does not speak for itself, it is a failure.\n\n- George\n|\nIntelligence and wisdom are certainly compatible, however they are rarely seen in each other’s company.\n\n- Craig\n|\nLove cannot be hidden. It even shines in the darkest places.' ~ Carla Olson Gade, The Shadow Catcher's Daughter\n\n- Carla\n|\nIt is better for the heart to break, than not to break.\n\n- Mary\n|\nSometimes life takes hold of one, carries the body along, accomplishes one's history, and yet is not real, but leaves oneself as it were slurred over.\n\n- D.H.\n|\nYou know me better than you think, you know, and you shall know me better yet.\n\n- C.S. Lewis, The Magician's Nephew\n|\nIgnorance is a very useful weapon in the hands of the devil against humanity, especially Christians.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, The Mountain of Ignorance\n|\nIf you ask me what I came to do in this world, I, an artist, will answer you: I am here to live out loud.\n\n- Émile\n|\nBut things change, people change, Gaby. Otherwise what would be the point of living?\n\n- Soheir Khashoggi, Nadia's Song\n|\nIf anyone on the verge of action should judge himself according to the outcome, he would never begin.\n\n- Søren Kierkegaard, Fear and Trembling\n|\nIf we are grateful, we shall be glad.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nWhether you think you're right or you think you're wrong. You're right.''If you think in pictures, write. If you think in words, paint.\n\n- Krista Kedrick, Under a Prairie Moon\n|\nExpansion. That is the idea the novelist must cling to. Not completion. Not rounding off, but opening out.\n\n- E.M. Forster, Aspects of the Novel\n|\nBut people need lift, too. People don't get moving, they don't soar, they don't achieve great heights, without someone buoying them up.\n\n- Elizabeth Wein, Rose Under Fire\n|\nWhoever you are, or whatever it is that you do, when you really want something, it's because that desire originated in the soul of the universe. It's your mission on earth.\n\n- Paulo Coelho, The Alchemist\n|\nI like to see the glass as half full, hopefully of jack daniels.\n\n- Darynda Jones, First Grave on the Right\n|\nMy dad always says, some people will treat you badly and you can't help that. But how you handle it and how it makes you feel, that's up to you.\n\n- Elise Broach, Shakespeare's Secret\n|\nHope and faith goes hand-in-hand, because without hope there is no faith. The same goes with want and needs, without any wants, there no need to have a need\n\n- Temitope\n|\nLife is here, death is over there. I am here, not over there.\n\n- Haruki Murakami, Norwegian Wood\n|\nAlas! I thought I had only a friendship for you, but the grief I now feel convinces me, that I cannot live without you.\n\n- Jeanne-Marie Leprince de Beaumont, Beauty and the Beast\n|\nThe better organized the state, the duller its humanity.\n\n- David Mitchell, Cloud Atlas\n|\nHonor,' he said firmly. 'I have great honor. So will you. But you will find that that is not the same as power.\n\n- Lois Lowry, The Giver\n|\nPeople with victim mentality get accustomed to life with an assistance of someone’s mind, waiting for someone to make decisions for him\n\n- Sunday\n|\nIn your pursuit of your passions, always be young. In your relationship with others, always be grown-up.\n\n- Tom\n|\nFor Reason, ruling alone, is a force confining; and Passion, unattended,is a flame that burns to its own destruction.\n\n- Kahlil Gibran, The Prophet\n|\nThis is the secret of life: the self lives only by dying, finds its identity (and its happiness) only by self-forgetfulness, self-giving, self-sacrifice, and agape love.\n\n- Peter Kreeft, Jesus-Shock\n|\nIf a religion cannot help a human wherever he or she stands, it is not of much use.\n\n- Abhijit Naskar, In Search of Divinity: Journey to The Kingdom of Conscience\n|\nTake responsibility of your own happiness, never put it in other people’s hands.\n\n- Roy T. Bennett, The Light in the Heart\n|\nTruth is as straight as an arrow, while a lie swivels like a snake.\n\n- Suzy Kassem, Rise Up and Salute the Sun: The Writings of Suzy Kassem\n|\nIf you ever find yourself in the wrong story, leave.\n\n- Mo Willems, Goldilocks and the Three Dinosaurs\n|\nWith patient hope, we can endure any hardship.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nIn the year 2025, the best men don't run for president, they run for their lives. . . .\n\n- Stephen King, The Running Man\n|\nTrust to some was placing all your insecurities and beliefs in one single person, and hoping he or she wouldn’t squash them.\n\n- Holly Hood, Prison of Paradise\n|\nChristmas, children, is not a date. It is a state of mind.\n\n- Mary\n|\nIf a man can tell if he's been successful in his life by having great friends, then I have been very successful.\n\n- Johnny\n|\nFaced with an exciting question, science tended to provide the dullest possible answer.\n\n- David Sedaris, Me Talk Pretty One Day\n|\nMost people like to talk about themselves, so get them going and you’ll make new friends quickly!\n\n- Amber Hurdle, The Bombshell Business Woman: How to Become a Bold, Brave, and Successful Female Entrepreneur\n|\nLove is a combination of friendship, passion, and respect.\n\n- John Glenn, John Glenn: A Memoir\n|\nGive me a book and I may change the world, give me a weapon and there will be no world to change.\n\n- Raouf\n|\nSadness is not the beginning or end of a process, but the lag between pleasure and happiness.\n\n- Isra\n|\nSaying 'I could have done more,' Zin, is what marks a man as a man and not a God.\n\n- R. Scott Bakker, The Darkness That Comes Before\n|\nWhen I was a little boy, they called me a liar, but now that I am grown up, they call me a writer.\n\n- Isaac\n|\nA castle of defense, a bastion of mightA fort where the wise teach the young to fightAn armory of weapons, sharp as hooksAre wrapped in leather and shelved as books\n\n- Shannon Hale, The Forgotten Sisters\n|\nOf all the weapons she had commanded, Elizabeth knew the least of love; and of all the weapons in the world, love was the most dangerous.\n\n- Seth Grahame-Smith, Pride and Prejudice and Zombies\n|\nMake improvements, not excuses. Seek respect, not attention.\n\n- Roy T. Bennett, The Light in the Heart\n|\nAn artist without ideas is a mendicant; barren, he goes begging among the hours.\n\n- Irving Stone, The Agony and the Ecstasy\n|\nAfter the end of the world, there is a world. Life doesn’t stop. It changes. And it changes me.\n\n- Caroline George, The Vestige\n|\nThe roots of the abundant life may seem bitter, but its fruits are sweet.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nTorque was the greatest thing in the world, as far as Lina was concerned.\n\n- Jaleigh Johnson, The Secrets of Solace\n|\nIf you hang out with chickens, you're going to cluck and if you hang out with eagles, you're going to fly.\n\n- Steve Maraboli, Unapologetically You: Reflections on Life and the Human Experience\n|\nLooking for Truth is not some kind of spazzy free-for-all, not even during this, the great age of the spazzy free-for-all.\n\n- Elizabeth Gilbert, Eat, Pray, Love\n|\nYet it's not for want of future that I'm here, he thought. It's for want of a present.\n\n- John le Carré, The Honourable Schoolboy\n|\nI wore your promise on my finger for one yearI'll wear your name on my heart til I dieBecause you were my boy, you were my only boy forever.\n\n- Coco\n|\nEvery moment of Life is a Challenge to Choose. Some Win, some Lose.\n\n- RVM\n|\nYou cannot control the behavior of others, but you can always choose how you respond to it.\n\n- Roy T. Bennett, The Light in the Heart\n|\nThe abundant life doesn’t happen by accident. It is the result of doing specific things purposefully every day and it requires an investment of time, energy and effort.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nDear fear, I’m divorcing you. Dear courage, I’m courting you. Dear hope, I’m pursuing you. Dear love, I’m marrying you.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nIt’s about freedom, joy, and wisdom. It’s all about divine love.\n\n- Harold Klemp, Spiritual Wisdom on Life after Death\n|\nA poet is, before anything else, a person who is passionately in love with language.\n\n- W.H. Auden, The Complete Works of W.H. Auden: Prose, Volume II: 1939-1948\n|\n... we are only ever pretending to ourselves, never to other people ...\n\n- José Saramago, The Cave\n|\nRead not to contradict and confute, nor to believe and take for granted ...but to weigh and consider.\n\n- Francis\n|\nAnd hope is like love...a ridiculous, wonderful, powerful thing.\n\n- Kate DiCamillo, The Tale of Despereaux\n|\nYour calling is calling you, are you answering?\n\n- Rob\n|\nI have a body, an emotional body and a mental body, but I am none of these. I am nothing and everything. I am an indivisible particle of oneness that can no longer be categorised\n\n- Ana\n|\nThe bards sing of love, they celebrate slaughter, they extol kings and flatter queens, but were I a poet I would write in praise of friendship.\n\n- Bernard Cornwell, The Winter King\n|\nSmartass Disciple: Which one was first created, time or things?Master of Stupidity: No things, no changes. No changes, no time.\n\n- Toba Beta, Master of Stupidity\n|\nThe truth is not always beautiful, nor beautiful words the truth.\n\n- Lao Tzu, Tao Te Ching\n|\nBe kind, for everyone you meet is fighting a hard battle.\n\n- Socrates\n|\nThe primary cause of unhappiness is never the situation, but you thoughts about it. Be aware of the thoughts you are thinking.\n\n- Eckhart Tolle, A New Earth: Awakening to Your Life's Purpose\n|\nMistakes are part of life. And yet, for some reason, most parents in this world, wish their children made no mistakes at all, or as little as possible.\n\n- Lukasz Laniecki, You Have The Right Not To Make Your Parents Proud. A Book Of Quotes\n|\nThe problem with escaping is that we leave behind us, even among those we love, different versions of the truth and everything we couldn’t bring ourselves to say.\n\n- Frederick\n|\nTo live an effective life, you must understand the essence and secret of life\n\n- Sunday\n|\nTo find the beauty of life, don’t complain, compliment.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nBodily exercise, when compulsory, does no harm to the body; but knowledge which is acquired under compulsion obtains no hold on the mind.\n\n- Plato, The Republic\n|\nUntil a man love God, can he love his neighbour.\n\n- Lailah Gifty, Akita\n|\nThrough many tributions, we begin to search for the truth.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nTo tell the truth is very difficult, and young people are rarely capable of it.\n\n- Leo\n|\nIf your success is not on your own terms, if it looks good to the world but does not feel good in your heart, it is not success at all.\n\n- Anna\n|\nSome people come into our lives and quickly go. Some stay for a while, leave footprints on our hearts, and we are never, ever the same\n\n- Flavia\n|\nCake is happiness! If you know the way of the cake, you know the way of happiness! If you have a cake in front of you, you should not look any further for joy!\n\n- C."